# Lorentz symmetry

## Statement

The framework's spacetime carries the Lorentz symmetry

$$\mathrm{SO}^+(3, 1) \;\cong\; \mathrm{SL}(2, \mathbb{C}) / \{\pm I\},$$

equivalently the $\mathrm{Spin}(3, 1)$ double cover of the identity
component.  This is the automatic consequence of complexifying the
spatial group $\mathrm{SL}(2, \mathbb{R})$ committed to in
[`sl2r_manifold`](sl2r_manifold.md), as carried in
[`minkowski_signature`](minkowski_signature.md).

## Derivation

Carried by [`minkowski_signature`](minkowski_signature.md).  The
standard Möbius action of $\mathrm{SL}(2, \mathbb{C})$ on the
forward null cone descends to a double cover of
$\mathrm{SO}^+(3, 1)$, giving signature $(3, 1)$: three spatial
dimensions (from [`three_dimensions`](three_dimensions.md)) and
one temporal dimension.

## Observational status

Lorentz symmetry is upheld in every precision test of special
relativity and field-theory consequences.  The Standard-Model
Extension (SME) framework of Kostelecky–Russell bounds potential
Lorentz-violating coefficients across all sectors; the
best-constrained parameters are at the $10^{-20}$ level or tighter.
No confirmed violation has been reported.

The framework does not predict Lorentz violation at any scale where
Proof A's continuum limit applies.  A confirmed violation would
require revising the topology commitment or the continuum
completion.

## Remarks

- "Exact" here refers to the structural claim.  The numerical
  bounds on potential violations are refinements *on top of* the
  structural prediction, not deviations from it.
- The $\mathrm{Spin}(3, 1)$ (rather than $\mathrm{SO}^+(3, 1)$)
  reading is what makes the framework's spinor content consistent;
  see [`klein_bottle`](klein_bottle.md) §Remarks for the
  half-integer-spin connection.
